Structural Resistance to Metric Failure

How u-Kama Addresses Goodhart, Campbell, Ashby, and Related Systemic Risks

Abstract

Complex systems frequently fail when decision making becomes dependent on simplified performance metrics. Once a metric becomes the target of incentives, actors begin optimising the metric rather than the underlying reality it was intended to measure. Over time the metric becomes detached from the phenomenon it was designed to represent.

This dynamic is captured in several well known principles:
	•	Goodhart’s Law
	•	Campbell’s Law
	•	Ashby’s Law of Requisite Variety
	•	Information asymmetry problems
	•	Principal–agent failures
	•	Moral hazard

The architecture of u-Kama is explicitly designed to resist these failure modes by grounding verification in ecological processes rather than financial or administrative metrics. The system combines independent witness convergence, Boolean ecological state gates, time based verification, and role separation to reduce the possibility of measurement distortion.

