1. Goodhart’s Law

Statement of the Law

Economist Charles Goodhart observed that:

“When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure.”

When institutions begin rewarding performance based on a measurable indicator, actors quickly discover ways to manipulate the indicator without improving the underlying system.

Examples appear across many domains:
	•	schools teaching to standardised tests rather than improving learning
	•	corporations maximising quarterly profit metrics at the expense of long term resilience
	•	environmental programmes focusing on easily measurable indicators such as tree counts rather than ecosystem health

Failure Mode

The failure arises because metrics become objects of optimisation rather than indicators of reality.

Once incentives depend on the metric, actors adapt their behaviour to maximise the measured variable.

The result is metric inflation rather than genuine improvement.

u-Kama Design Response

u-Kama reduces Goodhart vulnerability through several architectural choices.

Boolean ecological state gates
Instead of rewarding incremental improvements in numerical metrics, ecological state transitions resolve through simple conditions.

For example:
	•	water cycle functioning or failing
	•	nutrients retained or leaking
	•	biological community improving or degrading
	•	energy capture increasing or declining

Because the protocol recognises only whether ecological processes cross critical thresholds, the opportunity for incremental metric gaming is greatly reduced.

Independent witness convergence
Measurements are not accepted from a single source. Observational data, laboratory analysis, and human witnesses must converge before ecological state is recognised.

This prevents optimisation of a single measurement channel.

Time based validation
Ecological states must persist across seasonal cycles before recognition. Temporary metric manipulation is unlikely to survive environmental variation.

Together these features ensure that ecological reality rather than measurable indicators determines system outcomes.

