2. Campbell’s Law

Statement of the Law

Donald Campbell extended Goodhart’s observation into the domain of social policy.

He noted that:

“The more any quantitative social indicator is used for decision making, the more subject it will be to corruption pressures.”

Indicators that influence funding, promotion, or reputation become targets for manipulation.

Failure Mode

Campbell’s Law typically appears when organisations rely heavily on performance indicators tied to rewards.

Actors discover ways to increase reported performance without improving real outcomes.

This leads to distorted reporting, institutional gaming, and erosion of trust.

u-Kama Design Response

The architecture of u-Kama limits these incentives through structural separation.

Separation of ecological truth and financial flows
The system deliberately separates ecological verification from economic participation.

Ecological state recognition occurs independently of financial incentives.

Financial coordination instruments may operate around the ecological system but cannot influence state transitions.

Local resolution of ecological state
Each ecological cell resolves independently. Cells cannot compensate for one another.

This prevents aggregation effects that allow poor performance in one location to be hidden within broader averages.

Evidence transparency
All ecological claims are linked to publicly auditable evidence commitments.

Manipulation therefore requires falsifying multiple evidence streams rather than merely reporting improved indicators.

