3. Ashby’s Law of Requisite Variety

Statement of the Law

Cybernetician W. Ross Ashby formulated a principle describing how systems maintain stability in the presence of environmental complexity.

Only variety can absorb variety.

In practical terms, a control system must possess sufficient internal complexity to regulate the complexity of the environment it governs.

Failure Mode

Many governance systems attempt to control complex ecological or social systems using overly simplified models.

When the regulatory system lacks sufficient variety, it cannot respond effectively to environmental complexity.

The result is policy failure and system instability.

u-Kama Design Response

u-Kama incorporates variety through several mechanisms.

Multiple witness classes
Observational, laboratory, and human witnesses capture different aspects of ecological reality.

Each witness class operates through different methods and institutions.

This diversity increases the system’s capacity to detect ecological change.

Rich evidence layer
While the protocol state machine remains simple, the evidence layer may contain complex scientific measurements.

This allows ecological complexity to be observed without overcomplicating the verification logic.

Distributed landscape structure
Ecological cells operate independently across landscapes. Local ecological dynamics therefore remain visible rather than being averaged across regions.

Together these mechanisms provide the system with sufficient variety to respond to ecological complexity.

