4. Principal–Agent Problems

Problem Description

Principal–agent problems arise when decision makers act on behalf of others but possess different incentives or information.

Examples include:
	•	corporate executives acting in ways that benefit themselves rather than shareholders
	•	regulators captured by the industries they oversee
	•	project developers prioritising funding flows over ecological outcomes

u-Kama Design Response

The protocol architecture enforces strict role separation.

Key roles include:
	•	stewards responsible for ecological management
	•	witnesses responsible for verification
	•	custodians responsible for governance

No role controls both verification and economic benefit simultaneously.

This separation reduces opportunities for actors to manipulate outcomes for personal gain.

