5. Information Asymmetry

Problem Description

Information asymmetry occurs when one party possesses significantly more information about a system than others.

In environmental markets this problem is particularly acute because ecological conditions are difficult to observe remotely.

u-Kama Design Response

The Tritestium verification framework reduces information asymmetry by requiring independent evidence streams.

Remote sensing, laboratory analysis, and human observation collectively create a more complete picture of ecological condition.

Publicly auditable evidence commitments further reduce the information gap between observers and participants.

